* SCORE

- 4/5
  
* STRENGTHS
- The major contribution of this paper compared to Judd is that they
  tackled the problem of cross-bone traffic and had to work with
  multiple data centers.
- The deployment scale of this paper is very large. It covers 6 data
  centers, which handle large amounts of data.
- The experiment was carried out over 4 months, which is very
  extensive and reduces the noise of the data.
- The workloads were all real-world and not synthetic, which means
  these results are more transferrable to other works.
- The discussion about the mishaps and pitfalls is very transparent
  and may help future implementers avoid them.

* WEAKNESSES
- Usually, there is a graph showing the throughput sharing between
  DCTCP and CUBIC, as was the case in Judd. But that graph is
  missing. Judd noted that DCTCP starved CUBIC completely. The authors
  noted that they, too, noticed this phenomenon even when they fiddled
  with the threshold to prevent it. But more explanation would have
  been better.
- Considering the length of the paper, there were very few
  diagrams. Maybe some of the concepts could have been better
  visualized with a small diagram. For example, the differences
  between the two new ASIC queuing mechanisms.
- Very little was presented on the exploration of altering the base
  parameters of DCTCP.
- Possible solutions in cases where NIC-specific features, such as
  queue-per-host, are not available could have been explored.

* PAPER SUMMARY AND REVIEW

** Summary
In summary, the paper explains the deployment of DCTCP in a
large-scale, real-world data center setting.

** Motivation
The authors wanted to alleviate the aggressive response of older TCP
versions when seeing an ECN packet. Given the nature of traffic in
their data centers, they believe DCTCP will help them with burstiness.

** Implementation summary
*** How to change CCA for new connections
- Their initial implementation used eBPF programs that hooked into
  =sockops= to alter the CCA used based on the nature of the
  traffic. This was only supported in =linux kernel v4.11= and
  =cgroups-v2=. For older systems in their fleet, they set DCTCP as
  the default and used Traffic Control to turn off the ECN bits for
  non-DCTCP flows.

*** Existing connections
- Due to the nature of their data centers, they cannot simply
  terminate connections and establish new ones. To change CCA on the
  fly, they utilized a tool called *Maelstrom*.

*** Hardware Setup
- Since DCTCP and CUBIC use different metrics to identify congestion,
  it is important to separate them. This is possible in newer switches
  by just having separate queues. But in situations where it is not
  possible, they will have to share the queue.
- They found that the bottleneck was the ToR downlinks and focused on
  that.
- Those switches had the capability of marking ECN or doing
  Drop-tail/WRED depending on the ECN signal. So both CCAs got the
  correct signal, but they had to share the queue.
- The innate nature of DCTCP is to avoid long queues by reducing
  =cwnd= before the queue is full. The nature of CUBIC is that it only
  recognizes packet drops as a signal for congestion, hence filling up
  the queue.
- Due to this polar nature, they had to settle on a sub-optimal
  configuration for both CCAs—a high threshold for DCTCP and a low
  drop-tail threshold for CUBIC.
- This prevented CUBIC from filling up the buffer, and they found that
  minimizing DCTCP bursts was far more important than CUBIC,
  contradicting their initial prediction.
- Multi-host NICs needed the queue-per-host feature in the ToR for
  this to work.
- Depending on the mechanism in which the switches shared the buffer,
  there might be some irreconcilable configuration differences. This
  may be a vendor-by-vendor case.

*** Metrics
- They collected two different types of metrics: metrics from each
  layer of the network stack and metrics that covered various time
  periods—from RTT level to packet level to longer retransmission
  levels.
- They used eBPF to retrieve these statistics, as some of the
  kernel-level counters were found to be faulty.
- OS-level implementations such as TLP, TSO, and GRO caused some
  problems, which they had to debug.

*** Limitations
- One fundamental assumption was that the bottleneck was the ToR
  downlink, but there are situations in which that may not be the
  case.
- DCTCP is not a silver bullet. Due to the nature of some of the
  problems in congestion control, DCTCP is not able to solve all of
  them.

*** Conclusion
- DCTCP is effective in the real world, even in a very high-traffic,
  massive data center environment such as Meta.
- It is not trivial to change the CCA overnight. It may be a
  time-consuming process. Differences in OS implementations, different
  switch vendors, etc., contribute to inevitable non-trivial bugs.
- CCAs should be very simple, even when the network architecture is
  complex.
- Hotspots may occur in places not previously expected, and CCAs
  should have sensible defaults more forgiving than the ones
  calculated analytically.

** Review
They explained thoroughly the technical details of how to implement
DCTCP and discussed common pitfalls and some unexpected sources of
errors. They established that DCTCP works better than TCP in the real
world, large-scale setting.
- All in all, this is a very thorough paper with very few nitpicks,
  such as including diagrams and expanding on minor points.
